<font color="#FF0000">ETHICS AND THE &quot;OLD&quot; WARRIORS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 23:43:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art and Humming Eagle (Ed),<br><br>
First, I thank you for the dialog so far.  It has enlightened me and my family about how we can control circumstances through our thoughts and attitudes.  I am especially pleased to have read, and passed along to my family, the story of the fierce white and black wolves inside each of us, and our choosing food for one or the other.  <br><br>
More than that, however, is the insight I'm starting to understand more thoroughly concerning my tendency to take stands on ethical problems, especially when I see lives, or the health of an individual, involved in the problem.  My field of work (study) is occupational safety and health, and just over a year ago I lost my 18 year job because I wouldn't compromise my standards.  <br><br>
I appreciate the understanding very much that I have felt in the words above.  You have my thanks and respect for voicing that which I have had a difficult time explaining.  <br><br>
There are very few who understang the point of view many of us have after experiencing the Vietnam War, and its aftermath on us specifically.  I have told my boys that it was an experience that could either make one much stronger, or much weaker, depending upon how it was internalized.  <br><br>
The inner circle is very important to everyone, but most do not even realize that it exists.  How we interact with the world now is much dependent upon our prior experiences, and how we internalized those experiences.  <br><br>
I explained to my boys that before Vietnam, many of the Korean War POWs died in POW camps because they gave up.  But we (USAF aircrews) had training in how to conduct ourselves in a POW situation, and how to maintain our psychological health while a POW.  Because of this, the POW survival rate was much higher for Vietnam.  <br><br>
But that won't keep us from suffering stress when we find that our work has been dishonored by the very government that enlisted us to fight.  The abandonment of our allies, the subsequent fall of Vietnam, and the attitudes of the people in the States when we returned still hurts, and still haunts, many of us.  <br><br>
As Art has said, context means a lot.  But it is very difficult for those who did not serve in Vietnam to understand the context that the Vietnam Veteran places on his or her experiences.  It is likewise very difficult for those who did serve to understand the context of power, money and position that many in contemporary America place on their experiences.  <br><br>
It is perhaps not a coincidence that a majority of those who have recently gained fame and fortune have not served in the regular Armed Forces.
